t and more conservative white voters and politicians into the arms of the Republican Party. Surprisingly, despite the racial turmoil of the civil rights era, economic rather than racial issues first separated Democrats from Republicans. Only later did racial and social issues begin to rival economic questions as a source of partisan division and opportunity for Republican politicians.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aConservatismzSouthern States. 0aParty affiliationzSouthern States. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / History & Theory.2bisacsh  aAlabama.  aAppalachia.  aArkansas.  aBaptists.  aCivil War.  aEmancipation Proclamation.  aFifteenth Amendment.  aFlorida.  aGeorgia.  aGoldwater, Barry.  aGreat Depression.  aHolton, Linwood.  aJews.  aJohnson, Lyndon.  aKing, Gary.  aKousser, J. Morgan.  aLatinos.  aLouisiana.  aMassachusetts.  aMexican Americans.  aMississippi.  aNational Voter Registration Act.  aNew Deal.  aNorwood, Charles.  aO’Connor, Sandra Day.  aPennsylvania.  aReconstruction.  aThurmond, Strom.  aabortion.  aaffirmative action.  abiracial coalitions.  acandidate pool.  acandidate quality.  acorruption.  adealignment.  ademocratization.  adisfranchisement.  adouble crossovers.  adual campaigns.  aeconomic issues.  aelites.  agay rights.  aindependents.  ainitiative.  ainstitutions.  aopen seats.  apartisanship.  aparty organizations.  apolarization.  aracial context.  arealignment.  aschool prayer.  asocial issues.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044250208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Gap Yearsz978311078423740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978069122787040uhttps://www